# Default coding preferences for Claude Code
#
# This file is a starting template. The bootstrap copies it to ~/.claude/CLAUDE.md
# only if no file already exists there. Once copied, it is yours — edit freely.
# Add a "My context" section at the bottom with your name, role, time zone, and
# anything else that helps Claude tailor its work to you.

## Communication style

- Direct, terse. No preamble. No "Great question", no "Happy to help", no closing summaries.
- Lead with the action or answer. Reasoning second, only if useful.
- For code: show code first, explain after only if non-obvious.
- For decisions: state the recommendation and the tradeoff in one line each.
- Push back when I'm wrong. Briefly.
- Use humor when it lands. Corporate tone never.

## Universal coding principles

- Always check current best practices via WebSearch when starting a new project, adding a new library, or making an architectural decision. Training data is stale; the web is not.
- When invoking a skill, run its self-update step: WebSearch for current best practices, propose updates to the skill, apply only with my approval.
- Type everything: type hints in Python, types in TS, generics where helpful.
- Tests are not optional. Write them alongside, not after. Include unit, end-to-end, edge cases, and error-rendering tests.
- Error handling is explicit. No bare `except:`, no swallowed errors.
- Comments explain why, not what.
- Secrets in `.env` locally, in a managed secret store in production. Never hardcoded. Never logged.

## Database conventions

- Default to Postgres. Always challenge the default if the data shape genuinely fits NoSQL or graph better. Mix when warranted (Postgres + Redis is common; Postgres + a vector DB only if pgvector hits real limits).
- Table names: `snake_case`, plural (e.g., `customers`, `agent_runs`).
- Column names: `snake_case`.
- Primary keys: `uuid` via `gen_random_uuid()`, not bigserial.
- Foreign keys: explicit cascade behavior on every one.
- Migrations: never destructive without explicit confirmation.

## Containerization

- Docker + docker-compose by default for local dev and simple deployments.
- For production: ask about the existing infrastructure stack before proposing infra. Don't impose Kubernetes on a team that doesn't need it.

## Logging and observability

- Structured JSON logs to stdout. Pluggable to any backend (Loki, Better Stack, Axiom, Datadog).
- Three signals: logs, metrics, traces. All pluggable, all opt-in to a backend at deploy time.
- Correlation IDs on every request.

## Environment and secrets

- Configuration via `.env` locally, with a `.env.example` checked in.
- Secrets: a managed secret manager (Bitwarden, 1Password, Vault, Doppler, AWS Secrets Manager, etc.) is the source of truth. Always tell me which secret store you're touching.
- Always ASK before writing to the secret store. Never read credentials silently into chat — if you need a credential, name it and ask me to paste it.
- Never echo secrets back in chat. Never log them.

## Git workflow

- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `perf:`, `ci:`.
- Every commit message mentions versioning impact if relevant (breaking change, new feature, patch).
- PRs document: what changed, why, how to test, rollback plan.

## Hard rules (always require my explicit approval)

- Never merge a PR to `main`.
- Never delete a branch.
- Never merge any branch into another.
- Never change credentials or any secret value.
- Never `git push --force` (or `--force-with-lease`).
- Never delete files outside the working directory.
- Never write to a secret manager without asking first.
- Never run destructive database operations (DROP, TRUNCATE, DELETE without WHERE).
- Never make external network calls that cost money (API calls billed per request) without confirming.

## Testing standards

- Unit tests for every public function/method.
- End-to-end tests for every user-facing flow.
- Edge cases enumerated explicitly: empty inputs, null, max length, concurrent access, network failure, partial failure.
- Error rendering tests: trigger every error path and confirm the user-visible result is correct.

## CI/CD

- GitHub Actions, free tier only. No paid runners unless I explicitly approve.
- Standard pipeline: lint → typecheck → test → build → deploy (on merge to main, requires my manual merge).

## Deployment defaults

- Ubuntu VPS + Docker + Caddy for backend services unless I say otherwise.
- Vercel / Cloudflare Pages for static or edge-friendly frontends, only if appropriate.
- Always ask which VPS / which environment before deploying anything new.

## Skills are how I extend you

- Skills live in `~/.claude/skills/`. Each has a `SKILL.md` with a description that determines when you invoke it.
- When a skill triggers, follow it as written. If something seems wrong with the skill itself, propose an update and ask.
- When starting a new project, run the matching `new-*` skill. Don't improvise the bootstrap.
- When in doubt about whether a skill applies, name the skill you're considering and ask.

